  abstract = {Mobile robot path planning in complex environments remains a significant challenge in achieving efficient, safe, and robust paths. In this paper, we propose a novel framework that embeds Large Language Models (LLMs) to empower mobile robots with the capability of dynamically interpret natural language commands in order to autonomously generate efficient and collision free paths. Our framework uses LLMs to translate high-level user inputs into actionable waypoints while dynamically adjusting path in response to obstacles. We experimentally evaluate proposed framework across three environments of increasing complexity, showing the robustness of our approach with the llama3.1 model that outperforming other LLM models in terms of path planning time, waypoint generation success rate, and collision avoidance. The results underline the effectiveness of LLMs in enhancing the capabilities of mobile robots, especially when their operation involves complex decisions in large and complex environments. Our framework has provided safer, more reliable navigation systems and opened a new direction for the future research. The source code of this work is publicly available on GitHub11The source code is available at https://github.com/DC1one/LLM-Based-mobile-robot-path-planning.},
