  abstract = {At present, there are cognitive differences in situation understanding between officers on manned ships and maritime autonomous surface ships (MASSs). Traditional situation-understanding models rely on mathematical and logical relationships among parameters, making them struggle to handle unstructured data and dynamic scenarios. Therefore, this study proposes a human-like thinking mode for MASSs to understand encounter situations, and constructs a non-parametric situation-understanding model based on large language models (LLMs). Leveraging a modular framework and Tree-of-Thought prompting (ToT), the model effectively utilizes complex, low-quantitative information and generalizes across diverse encounter scenarios. Firstly, a modular nonparametric model tailored to different encounter situations is constructed. Secondly, environmental perception data is preprocessed to extract dynamic environmental information. Thirdly, prompts guide LLMs to retrieve relevant navigational knowledge; this knowledge is fused with environmental perception information. LLM prompts further drive multi-round interactions for reasoning, output generation, verification, and correction. Finally, this multi-round process achieves to understand the current encounter situation. Additionally, through comparative experiments, this study investigates how various LLMs and prompting methods impact the construction and application of non-parametric models. By shifting from quantitative modeling to non-parametric with human-like thinking ability, our approach offers a novel solution to ensure equitable navigational rights and safety for both MASSs and manned ships.},
